<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="n25173j"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n25" href="#n25173j">N25 (VI.B.15)</a>:  <a href="../../ff/fnbs/n25all.htm#n25173j"> 173(j)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> imper of v</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources">A careful study of the fifteen hundred roots found in Hebrew and Assyrian alike shows, however, that only about five hundred are &ldquo;perfect&rdquo;&mdash;that is to say, formed by three consonants&mdash;and that these are in fact double roots, used (just as in Chinese) to make the meaning more certain. The remainder&mdash;called &ldquo;defective,&rdquo; &ldquo;quiescent,&rdquo; and &ldquo;double&rdquo;&mdash;may easily be shown to have been originally monosyllables, especially by the <mark>imperative of the verbs</mark>, which represents the original exclamation. <small> Claude R. Conder, <a name="CRRM" href="../../ff/fdra/fdex.htm#CRRM"><cite title="source">The Rise of Man</cite></a> (1908) 39-40</small></blockquote> <mm class="note">Raphael transcription: <a name="c14117d" href="c14all.htm#c14117d">VI.C.14:117(d)</a> </mm></dd> </dd></dl>
